The story of Trebonius being seized by Dolabella at Smyrna is told by Appian (B. C. iii. 26), who says that a centurion cut off Trebonius' head as soon as he was taken. At daybreak Dolabella set up the head on the praetorian seat, from which Trebonius had been used to administer justice. lle was the first of Caesar's assassins, says Appian, who paid the penalty of his decds.
